 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Distance and Midpoint",
   "html": "$$\\text{Distance}=\\sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2+(y_2-y_1)^2}$$$$\\text{Midpoint}=\\left(\\dfrac{x_1+x_2}{2},\\ \\dfrac{y_1+y_2}{2}\\right)$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Find the distance between $(1,2)$ and $(4,6)$.",
     "a": "$d=\\sqrt{(4-1)^2+(6-2)^2}=\\sqrt{9+16}=\\sqrt{25}=5$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Gradient, Parallel & Perpendicular",
   "html": "$$m=\\dfrac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}$$<p>Parallel lines have <b>equal gradients</b>. Perpendicular lines have gradients whose product is $-1$: $m_1 m_2 = -1$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "A line has gradient $2/3$. What is the gradient of any line perpendicular to it?",
     "a": "$-3/2$ (since $\\tfrac{2}{3}\\cdot -\\tfrac{3}{2} = -1$)."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Equation of a Line",
   "html": "<p><b>Slope-intercept:</b> $y = mx + c$. <b>Point-slope:</b> $y - y_1 = m(x - x_1)$. <b>General:</b> $Ax + By + C = 0$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Find the equation of the line through $(2,3)$ with slope $4$.",
     "a": "$y - 3 = 4(x - 2) \\Rightarrow y = 4x - 5$."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
